{"key":"processedPost-12817711","value":{"id":12817711,"first":12816585,"last":12820884,"when":1277750027,"utime":"06/28/10 09:33 PM","cleanedPost":"To the OP, you can add gypsum to the soak, or as a pinch later when you load the jars.&nbsp; I prefer to add it to the soak water, but as long as you get some gypsum in there, you're fine.<br />Without a picture it's hard to diagnose the problem.<br />To Javadog, a 1/4\" hole is way too big for jar lids.&nbsp; Use four 1/16\" holes and the grains won't ever touch your filter.&nbsp; The 'greasy' appearance you're talking about is bacteria contamination.<br />An important thing to remember is if you shake a grain jar and it doesn't recover, it was already contaminated prior to the shake.&nbsp; The shake won't cause it.&nbsp; Also, don't fill jars more than 2/3 full to allow breathing air space for the mycelium, and shaking room for later.<br />RR"}}